SIMPLE: fatal
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fatal
<hw>Fa"tal</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>fatalis</ets>, fr.
<ets>fatum</ets>: cf. F. <ets>fatal</ets>. See <er>Fate</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Proceeding from, or appointed by, fate or destiny;
necessary; inevitable.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These thing are <qex>fatal</qex> and necessary.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was <qex>fatal</qex> to the king to fight for his money.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Foreboding death or great disaster.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That <qex>fatal</qex> screech owl to our house⟦br⟧
That nothing sung but death to us and ours.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Causing death or destruction; deadly; mortal;
destructive; calamitous; <as>as, a <ex>fatal</ex> wound; a
<ex>fatal</ex> disease; a <ex>fatal</ex> day; a <ex>fatal</ex>
error.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fatalism</ent>⟦br⟧
